title: Biodiversity patch/Priest quest
data:
The [Biodiversity patch](/wiki/Biodiversity_patch "Biodiversity patch") contains alternate home levels for the Priest quest, depending on the origin of the [pantheon](/wiki/Pantheon "Pantheon") the Priest serves (e.g. Mesoamerican for the Archeologist, Celtic for the Knight, etc.)

There are alternate home levels for all of the pantheons except the [Barbarian](/wiki/Barbarian "Barbarian") (whose pantheon comes from the [*Conan*](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conan_the_Barbarian "wikipedia:Conan the Barbarian") series by [Robert E. Howard](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_E._Howard "wikipedia:Robert E. Howard")), [Monk](/wiki/Monk "Monk") (from [Chinese mythology](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_mythology "wikipedia:Chinese mythology")), [Rogue](/wiki/Rogue "Rogue") (from [*Fafhrd and the Gray Mouser*](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fafhrd_and_the_Gray_Mouser "wikipedia:Fafhrd and the Gray Mouser") by [Fritz Leiber](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fritz_Leiber "wikipedia:Fritz Leiber")) and the [Samurai](/wiki/Samurai "Samurai") (from [Shinto](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shinto "wikipedia:Shinto")).

This level includes an opened [drawbridge](/wiki/Drawbridge "Drawbridge") over the river on the right side of the map. There are two [dart traps](/wiki/Dart_trap "Dart trap") inside the temple and four random traps throughout the level.

Each tree has a 50% chance of being a looted [banana](/wiki/Banana "Banana") tree, a 5% chance of being a banana tree that has not been looted (i.e. will produce bananas or [bees](/wiki/Killer_bee "Killer bee") if [kicked](/wiki/Kick "Kick")), and a 2% chance of being an [orange](/wiki/Orange "Orange") tree that has not been looted.

In addition to the standard twelve [human zombies](/wiki/Human_zombie "Human zombie"), the jungle includes three hostile [jaguars](/wiki/Jaguar "Jaguar").

Because the [Caveman](/wiki/Caveman "Caveman") pantheon is taken from Babylonian religion, the Caveman pantheon home level represents a [ziggurat](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ziggurat "wikipedia:Ziggurat"), a layered structure built for Mesopotamian temple complexes.

Each tree in the temple has a 33% chance of being an [orange](/wiki/Orange "Orange") tree and a 25% chance of being a [pear](/wiki/Pear "Pear") tree, and may or may not have been looted. All other trees will be nonspecific and will have been looted.

The temple includes [statues](/wiki/Statue "Statue") of a [sirrush](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sirrush "wikipedia:Sirrush") ([black dragon](/wiki/Black_dragon "Black dragon")), a [rothe](/wiki/Rothe "Rothe"), and two lions. Because the patch does not include lions as monsters, the last two are simply destroyed if [stone to flesh](/wiki/Stone_to_flesh "Stone to flesh") is cast on them.

The gap at the lower end of the outer wall of the temple contains a [boulder](/wiki/Boulder "Boulder") beside a [pit](/wiki/Pit "Pit"). There are two [dart traps](/wiki/Dart_trap "Dart trap") inside the temple, in addition to four random traps throughout the level.

This map is also used for the [Ranger](/wiki/Ranger "Ranger") pantheon, which is drawn from Roman mythology. A comment in the source indicates that this level represents a "pantheon" in a different sense of the word (i.e. a temple with images of multiple—not necessarily all—gods, like the [Pantheon in Rome](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pantheon,_Rome "wikipedia:Pantheon, Rome")).

The level map is a modified version of the home level of the [Healer quest](/wiki/Healer_quest "Healer quest") (the floor plan of the temple, in particular, is the same as that of the Temple of Epidaurus).

There are four [dart traps](/wiki/Dart_trap "Dart trap") inside the temple, in addition to six random traps throughout the level.

The [portal](/wiki/Portal "Portal") to the main dungeon will be located in the upper left corner of the map.

The river around the temple in the center of the map poses an obstacle for the Priest trying to reach the [Arch Priest](/wiki/Arch_Priest "Arch Priest"), but a resourceful player should not have difficulty finding a way across—[levitation](/wiki/Levitation "Levitation"), [jumping](/wiki/Jumping "Jumping"), [water walking](/wiki/Boots_of_water_walking "Boots of water walking"), a [wand of fire](/wiki/Wand_of_fire "Wand of fire") or [cold](/wiki/Wand_of_cold "Wand of cold"), a [scroll of earth](/wiki/Scroll_of_earth "Scroll of earth"), etc. The center of the map has eight [boulders](/wiki/Boulder "Boulder"), which can be used to bridge the water once the Priest gets inside.

Note that some of the water tiles on this map are [pools](/wiki/Pool "Pool") and some are [moats](/wiki/Moat "Moat"). Those below the temple are largely moats, with pools around the edges, while those above the temple and on either side are mostly pools. [The main difference](/wiki/Moat#Pool_vs._moat_vs._water "Moat") is that pools can be boiled away with [rays](/wiki/Ray "Ray") or [explosions](/wiki/Explosion "Explosion") of [fire](/wiki/Fire "Fire"), while moats can't.

Each tree has a 50% chance of being a looted [apple](/wiki/Apple "Apple") tree and a 25% chance of being an oak tree that may or may not have been looted (for acorns).

The level is considered a [swamp](/wiki/Swamp "Swamp"). Four [will o' wisps](/wiki/Biodiversity_patch#Bestiary "Biodiversity patch") will be randomly located throughout the level.

The map contains a [bear trap](/wiki/Bear_trap "Bear trap") and eight random traps.

A comment in the code indicates that the temple here includes references to each of the [nine worlds](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norse_cosmology "wikipedia:Norse cosmology") of Norse mythology.

The temple contains [statues](/wiki/Statue "Statue") of the [Norn](/wiki/Norn "Norn"), a lindworm ([white dragon](/wiki/White_dragon "White dragon")) named [Nidhogg](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nidhogg "wikipedia:Nidhogg"), [Freyr](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freyr "wikipedia:Freyr"), a [storm giant](/wiki/Storm_giant "Storm giant") named [Thyrm](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thyrm "wikipedia:Thyrm"), [Nerthus](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nerthus "wikipedia:Nerthus"), a [dwarf king](/wiki/Dwarf_king "Dwarf king") named [Modsognir](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modsognir "wikipedia:Modsognir"), [Lord Surtur](/wiki/Lord_Surtur "Lord Surtur"), an [ogre](/wiki/Ogre "Ogre") named [Hel](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hel "wikipedia:Hel"), and a leviathan ([blue dragon](/wiki/Blue_dragon "Blue dragon")) named [Jormungand](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jormungandr "wikipedia:Jormungandr"). Of these, Freyr and Nerthus do not correspond to creatures in the game; their statues will be destroyed if [stone to flesh](/wiki/Stone_to_flesh "Stone to flesh") is cast on them.

The Biodiversity patch contains alternate home levels for the Priest quest, depending on the origin of the pantheon the Priest serves (e.g. Mesoamerican for the Archeologist, Celtic for the Knight, etc.)

There are alternate home levels for all of the pantheons except the Barbarian (whose pantheon comes from the Conan series by Robert E. Howard), Monk (from Chinese mythology), Rogue (from Fafhrd and the Gray Mouser by Fritz Leiber) and the Samurai (from Shinto).

This level includes an opened drawbridge over the river on the right side of the map. There are two dart traps inside the temple and four random traps throughout the level.

Each tree has a 50% chance of being a looted banana tree, a 5% chance of being a banana tree that has not been looted (i.e. will produce bananas or bees if kicked), and a 2% chance of being an orange tree that has not been looted.

In addition to the standard twelve human zombies, the jungle includes three hostile jaguars.

Because the Caveman pantheon is taken from Babylonian religion, the Caveman pantheon home level represents a ziggurat, a layered structure built for Mesopotamian temple complexes.

Each tree in the temple has a 33% chance of being an orange tree and a 25% chance of being a pear tree, and may or may not have been looted. All other trees will be nonspecific and will have been looted.

The temple includes statues of a sirrush (black dragon), a rothe, and two lions. Because the patch does not include lions as monsters, the last two are simply destroyed if stone to flesh is cast on them.

The gap at the lower end of the outer wall of the temple contains a boulder beside a pit. There are two dart traps inside the temple, in addition to four random traps throughout the level.

There are four dart traps inside the temple, in addition to six random traps throughout the level.

The portal to the main dungeon will be located in the upper left corner of the map.

The river around the temple in the center of the map poses an obstacle for the Priest trying to reach the Arch Priest, but a resourceful player should not have difficulty finding a way across—levitation, jumping, water walking, a wand of fire or cold, a scroll of earth, etc. The center of the map has eight boulders, which can be used to bridge the water once the Priest gets inside.

Note that some of the water tiles on this map are pools and some are moats. Those below the temple are largely moats, with pools around the edges, while those above the temple and on either side are mostly pools. The main difference is that pools can be boiled away with rays or explosions of fire, while moats can't.

Each tree has a 50% chance of being a looted apple tree and a 25% chance of being an oak tree that may or may not have been looted (for acorns).

The level is considered a swamp. Four will o' wisps will be randomly located throughout the level.

The map contains a bear trap and eight random traps.

A comment in the code indicates that the temple here includes references to each of the nine worlds of Norse mythology.

The temple contains statues of the Norn, a lindworm (white dragon) named Nidhogg, Freyr, a storm giant named Thyrm, Nerthus, a dwarf king named Modsognir, Lord Surtur, an ogre named Hel, and a leviathan (blue dragon) named Jormungand. Of these, Freyr and Nerthus do not correspond to creatures in the game; their statues will be destroyed if stone to flesh is cast on them.
